Affect of varrying number of shots

Increasing the num_shots parameter makes the simulation take longer, but the growth is steady and linear.
"Shots" are essentially how many times we sample the quantum circuit to get a clear result. In a classical simulation,
the heaviest lift for the CPU is calculating the initial math for the quantum state. Once that hard work is finished, 
asking the computer to sample that result more often is relatively easy.

While a higher shot count is more demanding on the system, it doesn't cause the massive performance spikes that we
see when adding more qubits or increasing the volume depth.

